WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.100
So essentially, what we're going to talk about next is how we're trying to take steps to

00:00:06.100 --> 00:00:10.880
try to move ticlistamab and other bispecifics into the outpatient and community setting.

00:00:12.140 --> 00:00:17.960
So basically, I think I personally, and I suspect a lot of people on this panel, think

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:23.760
that bispecifics represent one of and likely the most transformative therapeutic modality

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:25.420
that we've come up with in myeloma to date.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:29.980
But community-level adoption of the bispecifics, these drugs have been approved now for

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:34.360
several years, and bispecific uptake in the community has been very limited by all sorts

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:35.280
of resource restraints.

00:00:35.420 --> 00:00:37.440
Tara, you know, Graf talked about this yesterday.

00:00:38.940 --> 00:00:43.960
And I think we live in a healthcare ecosystem where there's a huge risk for that inequity

00:00:43.960 --> 00:00:48.060
to become entrenched, for this to not be a barrier that we break down without real

00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:48.800
intentionality.

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:53.920
But I do think that with our current understanding of risk reduction and toxicity management,

00:00:53.920 --> 00:00:58.700
these are treatments that fundamentally can be given in almost any community setting with

00:00:58.700 --> 00:00:59.500
the right toolbox.

00:00:59.960 --> 00:01:04.820
So, you know, we talked about these, we led the conference with these curves because they

00:01:04.820 --> 00:01:06.220
are unbelievable.

00:01:06.580 --> 00:01:09.280
You know, these are treatments that we need to get to our patients.

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:14.880
I would posit that accelerating community-based bispecific adoption and trying to achieve

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:20.160
equity and access is fundamentally the highest impact goal that the myeloma research community

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:21.320
can currently undertake.

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:26.860
That if we, that the most myeloma life years gained will be by getting these drugs to more

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:29.000
patients as quickly as we possibly can.

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:31.180
So how do we do that?

00:01:31.920 --> 00:01:34.020
You know, Muhammad talked about some of these barriers already.

00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:38.740
You know, the primary barriers to community-based adoption include CRS reduction.

00:01:38.740 --> 00:01:41.080
That's the primary perceived adoption barrier.

00:01:42.160 --> 00:01:46.260
Hospitalization, you know, many centers, you know, beyond those costs, most of our community

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:48.880
docs, they just don't even have a hospital to admit a patient to.

00:01:48.980 --> 00:01:54.380
It's simply a non-starter to require hospitalization as part of the step-up process and get this

00:01:54.380 --> 00:01:56.120
to the majority of our community sites.

00:01:56.860 --> 00:01:59.920
And I would say that one opportunity that we often in our kind of academic research

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:03.940
and academic bubble don't talk about enough is the value of actually doing these trials

00:02:03.940 --> 00:02:05.000
in community sites.

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:06.940
It's easy to show what you can do.

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:07.760
I mean, no, it's not.

00:02:07.820 --> 00:02:11.020
It's not easy to show what you can do at the Mayo Clinic, but, you know, showing what you

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:14.700
can do at the Mayo Clinic, you know, immediately a community doc sees that and says, well,

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:15.280
that's not me.

00:02:15.380 --> 00:02:16.220
I can't do that.

00:02:16.300 --> 00:02:20.940
I can't operationalize what they did at MGH or MD Anderson or Mayo.

00:02:21.640 --> 00:02:22.320
That's not me.

00:02:22.440 --> 00:02:28.240
So, you know, we do know that one potent tool to reducing CRS risk is tocilizumab.

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:29.780
You know, we now have several.

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:31.360
You know, pieces of published data.

00:02:31.900 --> 00:02:35.660
We have the Amsterdam data from Majestic One and Compassionate Use Tech.

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:39.620
We have University of Miami, which was published in Blood Advances across multiple different

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:44.880
bispecifics, showing that you can dramatically reduce the rate of CRS, you know, to around

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.680
10 to 15 percent in these studies with prophylactic TOSI.

00:02:48.780 --> 00:02:54.800
These did, however, routinely involve the same observation that we would do in sort

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:58.620
of label, you know, hospitalization for subsequent monitoring and management.

00:02:58.880 --> 00:02:59.880
So we.

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:01.860
We wanted to push it a step further.

00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:05.280
So this is our outpatient Toclizumab or OPTEC trial.

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:10.060
This is a prospective phase two study that we've undertaken across our Sarah Cannon network,

00:03:10.060 --> 00:03:12.140
primarily along with Mohammed.

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:18.920
And basically what we did is we incorporated in the first arm, arm a prophylactic tocilizumab

00:03:18.920 --> 00:03:22.380
prior to first step up dosing of Toclizumab.

00:03:22.380 --> 00:03:29.200
And then patients were treated in an outpatient setting they needed to stay close to the outpatient

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:29.860
setting.

00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:50.740
They were, you know, within a we said a 30 minute radius while they were going through step up and first full dosing, they weren't allowed to drive, they needed to have caretaker support during that process, you know, between step up doses of Toclizumab, which Mohammed laid out the schedule for, you know, basically days one, four and eight, you know, patients needed to have daily check ins if those fell over the weekend, because these are the logistics that you need to figure out.

00:03:50.740 --> 00:03:58.740
Not all the clinics have our weekend access, so patients just got a phone call or a virtual virtual check in over the weekend and then essentially.

00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:09.200
You know, if they were sent home with a, you know, with a thermometer and a pulse ox, and they were asked to check their temperature and their oximeter twice a day.

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:10.000
And that was it.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:12.060
That was the amount of monitoring patients had.

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:28.640
And this was a trial that was performed across our Sarah Cannon network in in almost exclusively what you would consider to be community routine community settings, you know, so basically many of these sites had never done any by specific therapies, you know, certainly most of them had not done any by specific startups.

00:04:28.640 --> 00:04:29.820
So we went straight.

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:38.000
Into the community and had them go from the beginning of administering by specifics to doing this in an outpatient, you know, startup setting.

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:45.360
And so, you know, we do this is from last year's update at Soho, you know, first 24 patients, we had two CRS events.

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:47.840
So this is even lower than what's been described before.

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:50.560
I think what's happening is that we're looking less closely.

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:59.760
So we're picking up less, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, basically, you know, we have not had any patients who had breakthrough high grade.

00:04:59.760 --> 00:04:59.820
So we're picking up less maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, basically, you know, we have not had any patients who had breakthrough high grade.

00:04:59.820 --> 00:05:29.800
So we're picking up less maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, basically, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, maybe clinically insignificant CRS episodes, you know, but we're picking up less.

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:59.780
So we're picking up less.

00:05:59.780 --> 00:06:29.760
So we're picking up less.

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:34.000
Comparable to what we achieve with Tosi with something that's that's cheaper and easier to get.

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:53.280
So I think, you know, you know, the answer is we can definitely give by specifics in the community, you know, Tara talked about that, you know, you know, but I do think that, you know, we need to sort of develop research and dedicated tools so we can give our community docs just here is it's this is exactly how to do it to make it easy, safe in your center.

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:56.680
And I think that needs to be a big goal for what we're doing these days.

00:06:57.440 --> 00:06:58.220
Okay, thanks.
